## Bonus Questions (If You Finish Early)

### Question 8: Competitive Landscape
*"What are SelfPM's competitors? Why would someone choose SelfPM over them? What's your unfair advantage?"*

SelfPMs competitors, I’d say are other apps for ‘tracking’ — I say this because users dont yet know how much more valuable ‘observation’ can be compared to simple tracking. So, I’d say apps like Finch, maybe even Notion (you can definitely track + serve on notion, but you need to build your own observatbility infrastructure, unless someone has built it already , action item to MS to check on this, but still, you’d be on a platform with so many options, that, you have an option to track and observe. I think the lack of notifications, CPO analysis would make it depend very highly on user’s intrinsic motivation to succeed. 

Other competitors are probably just people who track on spreadsheets. And also observe themselves (ike I used to before). Possible, but lot of manual effort in generating the correct CPO reports (if they even though to do it), fragmented, and not scalable. 

Unfair advantage is that this is purpose build for understanding the ‘why’ behind failure. The analysis and relatability of the CPO reports, concept of enablers and targets, and  and the funnel to success as you graduate from observation to execution — this framework is the unfair advantage. It’s not a ‘game’. It’s real understanding. 

